{
  "doc_id": "26892",
  "text": "Similar to global trends (GBD 2015 Disease and Injury Incidence and Prevalence Collaborators 2016; [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , TI in the EMR disproportionately affect individuals who are in the economically productive age group of 15-44. This exerts an added pressure on the national economies of the EMR countries, especially those with limited resources [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The burden of TI is significantly higher in males than females. This gender ratio is consistent with global trends [CITATION_5] . Besides being a public health burden, TI are also associated with an immense economic burden; it is estimated to cost EMR countries a total of US$7.5 billion per year, equivalent to 1-1.5% of the GDP of most countries in the region [CITATION_6] .",
